MySQL Operators Documentation

This document provides a comprehensive list of all major MySQL operators with clear explanations and examples.

1. Arithmetic Operators

Addition (+) — Adds two numbers.

Example: SELECT 5 + 3;

Subtraction (-) — Subtracts one number from another.

Example: SELECT 10 - 4;

Multiplication (*) — Multiplies two numbers.

Example: SELECT 6 * 7;

Division (/) — Divides one number by another.

Example: SELECT 20 / 5;

Modulus (%) — Returns the remainder.

Example: SELECT 10 % 3;

2. Comparison Operators

Equal (=) — Checks if values are equal.

Example: SELECT * FROM users WHERE age = 25;

Not Equal (!= or <>) — Checks if values are not equal.

Example: SELECT * FROM users WHERE age != 25;

Greater Than (>)

Example: SELECT * FROM products WHERE price > 100;

Less Than (<)

Example: SELECT * FROM products WHERE price < 50;

Greater Than or Equal (>=)

Example: SELECT * FROM users WHERE score >= 80;

Less Than or Equal (<=)

Example: SELECT * FROM users WHERE score <= 60;

NULL-safe Equal (<=>) — Compares values including NULL.

Example: SELECT 1 <=> NULL;

3. Logical Operators

AND — True if both conditions are true.

Example: SELECT * FROM users WHERE age > 18 AND status = 'active';

OR — True if at least one condition is true.

Example: SELECT * FROM users WHERE city = 'NY' OR city = 'LA';

NOT — Negates a condition.

Example: SELECT * FROM users WHERE NOT status = 'inactive';

4. Bitwise Operators

Bitwise AND (&)

Example: SELECT 5 & 3;

Bitwise OR (|)

Example: SELECT 5 | 3;

Bitwise XOR (^)

Example: SELECT 5 ^ 3;

Bitwise NOT (~)

Example: SELECT ~5;

Left Shift (<<)

Example: SELECT 5 << 1;

Right Shift (>>)

Example: SELECT 5 >> 1;

5. Assignment Operators

= — Assigns a value.

Example: SET @x = 10;

:= — Assigns a value in expressions.

Example: SELECT @y := 20;

6. String Operators

Concatenation (CONCAT)

Example: SELECT CONCAT('Hello', ' World');

LIKE — Pattern matching.

Example: SELECT * FROM users WHERE name LIKE 'A%';

NOT LIKE

Example: SELECT * FROM users WHERE name NOT LIKE '%son';

REGEXP / RLIKE — Regular expression matching.

Example: SELECT * FROM users WHERE name REGEXP '^A';

7. Logical/Flow Operators

IN — Matches any value in a list.

Example: SELECT * FROM users WHERE id IN (1, 2, 3);

NOT IN

Example: SELECT * FROM users WHERE id NOT IN (4, 5);

BETWEEN — Checks if value is within a range.

Example: SELECT * FROM products WHERE price BETWEEN 100 AND 500;

NOT BETWEEN

Example: SELECT * FROM products WHERE price NOT BETWEEN 100 AND 500;

IS NULL

Example: SELECT * FROM users WHERE email IS NULL;

IS NOT NULL

Example: SELECT * FROM users WHERE email IS NOT NULL;

8. Other Useful Operators

EXISTS — Checks if a subquery returns rows.

Example: SELECT * FROM users WHERE EXISTS (SELECT id FROM orders WHERE users.id = orders.user_id);

ANY / SOME — Compares a value to any value in a list.

Example: SELECT 10 > ANY (SELECT age FROM users);

ALL — Compares a value to all values in a list.

Example: SELECT 10 > ALL (SELECT age FROM users);


